Use **`WebApplicationFactory<TEntryPoint>`** from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing`. It hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` — no real port, no real server.

**1. Add the NuGet package:**
```
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
```

**2. Write a test (xUnit example):**
```csharp
public class McpServerTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpServerTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2.0", body.GetProperty("jsonrpc").GetString());
        Assert.True(body.TryGetProperty("result", out _));
    }
}
```

**3. If using SSE (Streamable HTTP):**
```csharp
[Fact]
public async Task ListTools_OverSse()
{
    var request = new { jsonrpc = "2.0", id = 2, method = "tools/list" };
    var content = JsonContent.Create(request);
    content.Headers.Add("Accept", "text/event-stream");

    var response = await _client.SendAsync(
        new HttpRequestMessage(HttpMethod.Post, "/mcp") { Content = content },
        HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead);

    var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
    using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);

    // Parse SSE events
    string? line;
    var events = new List<string>();
    while ((line = await reader.ReadLineAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (line.StartsWith("data: "))
            events.Add(line[6..]);
    }

    Assert.NotEmpty(events);
    var result = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<JsonElement>(events[0]);
    Assert.True(result.TryGetProperty("result", out _));
}
```

**Key points:**
- `WebApplicationFactory` uses your real `Program` startup — middleware, DI, routing all run as in production
- No TCP port is opened; requests go through an in-memory transport
- Make `Program` visible to your test project with `InternalsVisibleTo` or a `public partial class Program { }` marker
- For **stateful sessions** (MCP session IDs), reuse the same `HttpClient` instance across calls and track the `Mcp-Session-Id` header
